The center of the ellipse is the midpoint of the segment connecting the foci, which is $(2,4).$  Thus, $(h,k) = (2,4).$  The distance between the foci is 4, so $2c = 4,$ which means $c = 2.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair F1, F2, P, C;

F1 = (2,2);
F2 = (2,6);
P = (14,-3);
C = (2,4);

draw(Circle(C,sqrt(100 + 16)));
draw(F1--F2);
draw(C--P);

dot("$F_1$", F1, SW);
dot("$F_2$", F2, NE);
dot("$P$", P, SE);
dot("$C$", C, N);
[/asy]

Since the ellipse passes through $(14,-3),$
\[100 = (14 - 2)^2 + (-3 - 4)^2 = a^2 + b^2.\]Also, $b^2 = a^2 - c^2 = a^2 - 4.$  Then $100 = a^2 + (a^2 - 4),$ so $a^2 = 52.$  Hence, $b^2 = 48.$

Final Answer: $\boxed{(2\sqrt{13}, 4\sqrt{3}, 2, 4)}.$

